The article discusses the recent votes to raise the debt limit, which is seen as a positive step to avoid a default that would negatively impact the economy and working families. President Biden is eager to sign the bill once it passes the House. The focus remains on swiftly passing Biden's economic agenda and making investments in jobs, competitiveness, and lower prices for the middle class. The article emphasizes that raising the debt limit is a shared responsibility and not directly related to Biden's economic plans. It calls for Congress to continue addressing the debt limit in the future to ensure America's bills are paid. The article acknowledges the efforts of the 11 Republicans who helped end the filibuster and urges more Republicans to responsibly address the debt limit instead of choosing default or obstruction. It emphasizes the need to avoid partisan politics and prevent the routine process of paying bills from becoming a confidence-shaking political showdown.